<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Originally described from Madeira, with a circumtropical distribution. However, reports of this species show a high polymorphism of specific characters (
<bibRefCitation author="Radashevsky, Vasily I." journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="375 - 384" title="Life history, morphology and distribution of Dipolydoraarmata (Polychaeta: Spionidae)" volume="83" year="2003">Radashevsky and Nogueira 2003</bibRefCitation>
). It has been suggested that at least two allopatric species are present under the name 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Dipolydora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dipolydora armata" order="Spionida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="armata">Dipolydora armata</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Blake, J. A." journalOrPublisher="Antarctic Research Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="205 - 288 - 205 - 288" title="Polychaetes of the family Spionidae from South America, Antarctica, and adjacent seas and islands" volume="39" year="1983">Blake 1983</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Bick, Andreas" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="177 - 187" title="The morphology and ecology of Dipolydoraarmata (Polychaeta, Spionidae) from the western Mediterranean Sea" volume="82" year="2002">Bick (2002)</bibRefCitation>
distinguishes three morphological forms amongst Western Mediterranean material on the basis of notopodial spines, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Radashevsky, Vasily I." journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="375 - 384" title="Life history, morphology and distribution of Dipolydoraarmata (Polychaeta: Spionidae)" volume="83" year="2003">Radashevsky and Nogueira (2003)</bibRefCitation>
attribute this variability to stages of asexual reproduction of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
